<h2>North Dakota Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>North Dakota offers several valuable incentives for solar and HVAC installations, making energy upgrades more affordable for homeowners throughout the state:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> The 30% federal tax credit applies to the total cost of solar installations, including equipment, labor, and permits. This credit can be claimed for systems installed through 2032, with the percentage stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. Homeowners can carry forward unused credits to future tax years, and the credit applies to both primary and secondary residences.</li>

<li><strong>North Dakota Renewable Energy Tax Credit:</strong> The state provides up to \$3,000 in tax credits for renewable energy systems, including solar panels and geothermal HVAC systems. This credit can be combined with the federal ITC for maximum savings and applies to both new installations and system expansions.</li>

<li><strong>Xcel Energy Solar Rewards Program:</strong> Xcel Energy customers can receive upfront rebates of \$0.50-1.00 per watt for qualifying solar installations, plus ongoing production incentives. The utility also offers time-of-use rates that can increase solar savings for customers with battery storage systems.</li>

<li><strong>Local Utility HVAC Rebates:</strong> Many North Dakota utilities offer rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, including \$300-800 for ENERGY STAR furnaces, \$500-1,500 for heat pump systems, and up to \$2,000 for geothermal installations. These programs often include financing options with reduced interest rates.</li>

<li><strong>USDA Rural Development Grants:</strong> Rural North Dakota residents may qualify for USDA Rural Energy for America Program (REAP) grants covering up to 25% of solar and energy efficiency project costs, which can be combined with other incentives for substantial savings.</li>
</ul>

