    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">How much do solar panels cost in North Dakota?</h3>
    <p>Solar panel costs in North Dakota typically range from \$2.80-3.50 per watt installed, making a typical 6kW residential system cost \$16,800-21,000 before incentives. After applying the 30% federal tax credit and state renewable energy credit, homeowners can expect to pay \$9,800-14,700 net cost. Factors affecting pricing include system size, equipment quality, roof complexity, and local installer competition. Financing options include solar loans, leases, and power purchase agreements, though purchasing provides the best long-term value given North Dakota's incentive structure.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">What SEER rating is recommended for North Dakota?</h3>
    <p>For North Dakota's climate, SEER ratings of 14-16 are typically adequate for most homes, as cooling loads are moderate compared to southern states. However, SEER 18+ systems can provide additional savings during hot summer periods and often qualify for utility rebates. More important than SEER rating is the system's heating efficiency (HSPF for heat pumps, AFUE for furnaces), as heating represents 60-70% of annual HVAC energy use. Cold-climate heat pumps with HSPF ratings above 9.0 are recommended for optimal year-round performance.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Do solar panels work in North Dakota winters?</h3>
    <p>Solar panels work very effectively in North Dakota winters, often producing more electricity per hour of sunshine than during hot summer days due to improved efficiency in cold temperatures. Snow typically slides off tilted panels quickly due to the state's frequent temperature fluctuations and wind. While daylight hours are shorter in winter, the combination of snow reflection, clear skies, and efficient cold-weather operation means winter production is substantial. Most North Dakota solar systems produce 15-25% of their annual output during winter months.</p>
